Here are both approaches using Shell navigation and `IQueryAttributable`:

## 1. Route registration (AppShell.xaml.cs)

```csharp
public partial class AppShell : Shell
{
    public AppShell()
    {
        InitializeComponent();
        Routing.RegisterRoute("productdetails", typeof(ProductDetailsPage));
    }
}
```

## 2. ProductListPage — navigate on tap

```xml
<!-- ProductListPage.xaml -->
<CollectionView ItemsSource="{Binding Products}"
                SelectionMode="Single"
                SelectionChangedCommand="{Binding ProductSelectedCommand}"
                SelectionChangedCommandParameter="{Binding SelectedItem,
                    Source={RelativeSource Self}}">
    <CollectionView.ItemTemplate>
        <DataTemplate x:DataType="models:Product">
            <VerticalStackLayout Padding="10">
                <Label Text="{Binding Name}" FontSize="18" />
                <Label Text="{Binding Price, StringFormat='${0:F2}'}" />
            </VerticalStackLayout>
        </DataTemplate>
    </CollectionView.ItemTemplate>
</CollectionView>
```

```csharp
// ProductListViewModel.cs
public partial class ProductListViewModel : ObservableObject
{
    [ObservableProperty]
    ObservableCollection<Product> products;

    [RelayCommand]
    async Task ProductSelected(Product product)
    {
        if (product is null) return;

        // ── Approach A: query-string parameter (string ID) ──
        await Shell.Current.GoToAsync($"productdetails?id={product.Id}");

        // ── Approach B: pass the full object ──
        var parameters = new ShellNavigationQueryParameters
        {
            { "product", product }
        };
        await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("productdetails", parameters);
    }
}
```

## 3. Receiving data — IQueryAttributable on the ViewModel

```csharp
// ProductDetailsViewModel.cs
public partial class ProductDetailsViewModel : ObservableObject, IQueryAttributable
{
    private readonly IProductService _productService;

    [ObservableProperty]
    Product product;

    public ProductDetailsViewModel(IProductService productService)
    {
        _productService = productService;
    }

    public void ApplyQueryAttributes(IDictionary<string, object> query)
    {
        // Approach A: string ID → load from service
        if (query.TryGetValue("id", out var idObj))
        {
            string id = idObj.ToString();
            Product = _productService.GetProduct(id);
        }

        // Approach B: full object passed directly
        if (query.TryGetValue("product", out var productObj)
            && productObj is Product p)
        {
            Product = p;
        }
    }
}
```

## 4. Wire up the details page

```xml
<!-- ProductDetailsPage.xaml -->
<ContentPage xmlns:vm="clr-namespace:MyApp.ViewModels"
             x:DataType="vm:ProductDetailsViewModel">
    <VerticalStackLayout Padding="20">
        <Label Text="{Binding Product.Name}" FontSize="24" />
        <Label Text="{Binding Product.Price, StringFormat='${0:F2}'}" />
        <Label Text="{Binding Product.Description}" />
    </VerticalStackLayout>
</ContentPage>
```

```csharp
// ProductDetailsPage.xaml.cs
public partial class ProductDetailsPage : ContentPage
{
    public ProductDetailsPage(ProductDetailsViewModel vm)
    {
        InitializeComponent();
        BindingContext = vm;
    }
}
```

**Key differences:**

| | Query string (`?id=`) | `ShellNavigationQueryParameters` |
|---|---|---|
| **Data type** | Serialized as string | Any object, passed by reference |
| **Use when** | Simple IDs, primitives | Complex objects, avoiding re-fetch |
| **Deep-link safe** | ✅ Yes | ❌ No (objects can't come from a URI) |

Both arrive in the same `ApplyQueryAttributes` method — just check which key is present. Always `await` `GoToAsync` to avoid race conditions.
